version.name: Barb Jungr
version.description: Barb Jungr has been compared to Nina Simone, Peggy Lee and Edith Piaf and is coming to our shores so that we can see for ourselves what this widely celebrated singer is capable of. Known for her singular interpretations of classic popular songs this show will give listeners a whole new perspective on old favourites.

version.name: Jonah and the Wailers
version.description: Regulars at the Basement, Jonah and the Wailers have recorded 8 live CD's there, in as many years performing. The group which tours around folk and arts festivals is joined by the Elementals, for a night of uplifting choral music.

version.name: Misinterprotato
version.description: Mesmerizing driving rhythms are what makes Misinterprotato's sound so unique. No strangers to Sydney audiences, the trio who have previously frequented jazz festivals around the country, are bringing their cool lounge jazz to the Basement in September.

version.name: Wolf Mail
version.description: International musician Wolf Mail was awarded "best blues guitarist" in 2005 by Japan's Guitar Player magazine. Bust out your leather jacket, pull your pants up high and sit back as Mail transports you back into the fifties with his award winning music.

event.name: Finoa Joy Hawkins and Blue Dream

version.name: Finoa Joy Hawkins and Blue Dream
version.description: Award winning Pianist Fiona Joy Hawkins is known for her soothing contemporary classical works. The Aria nominee is joined by Blue Dream, a collective of improvisational musicians who helps bring Hawkins music to life.

version.name: Lil' Band O Gold
version.description: Swamp dogs and blues boys unite in this all star band of highly accomplished musicians from the southern states of the USA. The coming together of this magical group was captured in the acclaimed documentary, ‘The Promised Land’ which has been re-pressed due to popular demand. Following their reception at the East Coast Blues and Roots Festival these lads are back for another bite at the cherry with 2 shows in Sydney.

version.name: Lil' Band O' Gold
version.description: The Louisiana super group are returning for shows all over the country including their first appearance in Sydney.

version.name: Paul Dempsey
version.description: As an offshoot of his tour with Powderfinger, Paul Dempsey has added some solo, acoustic shows in Sydney and Melbourne. The Something For Kate frontman's debut solo album Everything is True was nominated for 3 Arias and won iTunes Australian Album of the Year. If floppy haired, whisky voiced, singer-songwriters are your style then Paul Dempsey just may be your god.

version.name: Dan Kelly
version.description: It has been a long wait but Dan Kelly has finally released his solo album, Dan Kelly's Dream, and is now setting out on a massive national tour. Head to the Annandale and catch the insightful yet kooky lyricism of Dan Kelly as he tries to make music, entertain the masses and save the planet, all at once.

version.name: Cancer Bats
version.description: Cancer Bats fans, rejoice: if you were a little nonplussed at the thought of shelling out to see them do a support slot for Bullet For My Valentine, be advised that the 'Bats are doing their own headline gig at the Annandale while they're in town.

version.name: MM9
version.description: Sydney act MM9 or Many Machines On Nine perform at the Gaelic on the back of their new album The Air Between released in March.

event.name: In Search of Sunrise: South Africa

version.name: In Search of Sunrise: South Africa
version.description: Trance lovers, your time has come! Taking over from Tiesto, Richard Durand is manning the decks at the revived ISOS event at the Gaelic along with Jonas Stenberg and Trent McDermott.

version.name: Horrorshow
version.description: After appearances supporting Hilltop Hoods in England and Germany (July), as well as a spot on the sold out Splendour in the Grass, Horrorshow will be performing in Sydney's CDB.

version.name: GBH and The Rumjacks
version.description: There isn't a self-respecting gutter punk, hardcore kid or subcultural miscreant alive who hasn't seen the GBH logo emblazoned on the back of a leather jacket, a denim vest, or a torn-up t-shirt.

version.name: Louis Bertignac
version.description: Red, white and blues. Those are the national colours of french blues guitarist Louis Bertignac from outfit Telephone. Now a solo artist he has been referred to as the Gallic Kieth Richards.

version.name: Halloween Syndicate
version.description: A full costume themed night made up of a cabaret hour and performances from Psyconanny & The Baby Shaker Halloween Syndicate features a variety of small acts from burlesque to natations to belly dancing. Supports Pute Madre Brothers .

version.name: Coffins
version.description: Japanese metal 3 piece visit Sydney on their Australian tour.

version.name: The Wonder Years
version.description: The Wonder Years will tour Australia this September for the First time. On the Hits, Tits and Pits Tour. Joining them on this PopPunk whip around Australia will be acts: Heroes For Hire, Tonight Alive and Skyway.

version.name: Dream Home
version.description: Eleven photomedia artists take a critical look at what a 'dream home' means for different Australians.

version.name: Kaoru Alfonso: 212
version.description: The 212-unit Currong project produced the tallest building in Canberra and at the time was considered an innovative approach to meet the city's changing housing needs. In this exhibition, all 212 windows of the Currong flats have been photographed and gridded on the gallery wall.

version.name: Bindi Cole: Sistagirls
version.description: Bindi Cole’s portraits and Jirra Lulla Harvey’s accompanying texts offer an insight into the world of the Sistagirls, a small community of Indigenous transgender women.

version.name: A Little Bazaar
version.description: Dead Space Living Artists (DSLA) are hosting a hand-made market as part of the Paddington Alive Fashion Festival. Head to the ACP to see the hand-made gems of 18 local designers including Nicked Design, Jelly, Jessica Stewart, Bilingual, shãshen, Treasure and Mok’s studio. It's also your last chance to catch the ACP's Zeitgeist Becomes Form, London Calling and The Birthday Suit exhibitions.

version.name: Liverpool City Art Prize 2010
version.description: An open-themed, $10,000 art prize open to all artists.

version.name: Liverpool Art Society 2010
version.description: The popular annual Liverpool Art Society exhibition showcases the diverse range of art created by members of the Liverpool Art Society Inc. This year, the exhibition is united by the theme 'Memories, Characters and Places of Liverpool.'

event.name: Mil-Pra AECG Aboriginal Exhibition & Art Award

version.name: Mil-Pra AECG Aboriginal Exhibition & Art Award
version.description: A competition open to all Indigenous and Torres Strait Islander people living in NSW and the ACT. In 2010 the theme of the exhibition is 'Legends of the Dreaming.'

version.name: Shifting Sands
version.description: Local and foreign artists explore the Botany Bay region through a range of media.

version.name: Primavera 2010
version.description:
The MCA's annual exhibition for Australian artists 35 and under is curated in 2010 by Katie Dyer and features Akira Akira, Jule Fragar, Agatha Gothe-Snape, Alasdair McLuckie, James Newitt, Jackson Slattery and Emma White.
.

version.name: Runa Islam
version.description: Film installations by a Bangladesh-born UK artist.

event.name: In the Balance: Art for a Changing World

version.name: In the Balance: Art for a Changing World
version.description: An exhibition featuring works by Australian and international contemporary artists that address ecological issues.

version.name: 16 Degrees
version.description: 16 artists from the Charlie Sheard Studio School apply modern inspiration to the traditional painting techniques of the 'Old Masters'.

version.name: Sonya Rothwell: armour&more
version.description: A series of figurative works that capture sensual figures and faces.

event.name: A List Comedy at the Oatley Hotel

version.name: A List Comedy at the Oatley Hotel
version.description: The fine, upstanding proprietors of the Oatley Hotel are here to rescue you from hump day blues with some of the best and brightest on the comedy circuit. Featuring the comedic styling of Matt Dyktynski, James Rochford, and Dolores Lorette.

version.name: Yellow Moon
version.description: The story of a Glaswegian Bonnie and Clyde is told through physical theatre.

version.name: Fool for Love
version.description: In a claustrophobic motel room on the edge of California’s Mojave Desert, two lovers tear themselves – and each other – apart in this confronting play.

version.name: The Sweetest Thing
version.description: The premier of this new Australian work, a story of a grieving family seen through the fram of chaos theory.

version.name: A Distressing Scenario
version.description: A double bill of devised pieces Everything I Know About the Global Financial Crisis in One Hour and The Market Is Not Functioning. The night will examine the cultural repercussions of the current economic state.

version.name: Fame - The Musical
version.description: FAME – The Musical is the story of a diverse group of students at New York City’s celebrated High School of the Performing Arts. Meet the class of 2010 in this new production.

version.name: Tap Dogs
version.description: Winner of 11 major international awards including an Olivier for Best Choreography, Tap Dogs arrives at the Capitol Theatre this summer.

version.name: Rain Man
version.description: Charlie Babbitt discovers he has an autistic older brother and goes on a road trip of discovery, love and understanding.

version.name: Australia: The Show
version.description: A light-hearted interrogation of Australian history with a couple of larrikins.

version.name: Lotte's Gift
version.description: A touching recollection of memoirs, memories and the relationship between grandmother and granddaughter.

event.name: Peace Train - The Cat Stevens Story

version.name: Peace Train - The Cat Stevens Story
version.description: Enjoy live performances from the Firecats as they and Darren Coggan explore the man behind the music.

version.name: Burnt by the Sun
version.description: Based on the Oscar-winning film, this play is set in Russia in the 1930s, where a family is gradually threatened by military and human enemies.

version.name: Katie Noonan
version.description: Australian jazz darling Noonan will perform songs from the Emperor's Box with guitarist Cameron Deyell. Also featuring performances from Charmaine Ford Trio, and George Garzone with The Mike Nock Trio.

version.name: List Operators
version.description: Recently nominated for 'Best Show' at the 2010 Melbourne International Comedy Festival, the List Operators bring their child-friendly show to Sydney. Involving farts and silly fun, this show is sure to bring out the kid in anyone.

event.name: Andrea Keller Quartet w Bernie McGann/Warwick Alder, George Garzone with The Mike Nock Project

version.name: Andrea Keller Quartet w Bernie McGann/Warwick Alder, George Garzone with The Mike Nock Project
version.description: Boston's George Garzone helps top off SIMA's Jazz Visions festival, playing saxophone with Sydney's own Mike Nock Project at the Seymour Centre's Everest Theatre. Melbourne's Andrea Keller Quartet open the show.

event.name: Charmaine Ford Trio, Katie Noonan & Cameron Deyell, George Garzone with The Mike Nock Trio

version.name: Charmaine Ford Trio, Katie Noonan & Cameron Deyell, George Garzone with The Mike Nock Trio
version.description: New Zealand-born pianist Charmaine Ford opens an evening featuring singer-songwriter Katie Noonan, George Garzone and the Mike Nock Trio. The performance will go on at the Seymour Centre's Everest Theatre as part of SIMA's Jazz Visions festival.

version.name: Growing Friends Spring Plant Sale
version.description: Head to Mount Annan Botanic Garden to buy grasses, wattles, eucalypts, grevilleas and other plants native to the gardens.

version.name: Draw
version.description: Drawings by artists French, Stefan Marx and Marcus Oakley.

version.name: Brent Grayburn: Roadside Picnic
version.description: A video sculpture that journeys to the edge of an invaded forest where a nervous picnicker squirms in a state of high agitation amongst a landscape of ever compressing whiteness and discarded debris, 'Roadside Picnic' is infested with detachment and voodoo. Shot in reverse and constructed backwards, Roadside Picnic is the book written by Russian novelists Boris and Arkady Strgatsky and is credited by Andrei Tarkovsky for nothing other than the words Stalker and Zone.

version.name: Tim Silver
version.description: Within his practice, Silver frequently explores notions of entropy, decay and the passing of time through processes of casting and photographic documentation. Born in Hobart, Tim Silver currently lives and works in Sydney.

version.name: Stereotyped
version.description: An experimental exhibition of typography and sound that challenges to definition of 'designer' by bringing together composers, graphic designers, film makers, sound engineers, typographers, and musicians.

version.name: Toni Warburton/Trevor Fry
version.description: In this joint exhibition Toni Warburton's Picture Window exhibits a collection of things salvaged from a house fire and Trevor Fry's employs archaic and ancient coil-building techniques for his new ceramic sculptures.

version.name: Francesca Heinz: Performance #1
version.description: The New Zealand artist will make herself a new skin, follow a strict diet and become increasingly restricted by the presence of the 'Minder' for three consecutive days. The performances may be viewed from outside of the Gallery through peep holes.

event.name: Stormie Millks: In Celebration of Second Best

version.name: Stormie Millks: In Celebration of Second Best
version.description: Beginning on the street and going on to exhibit artwork the world over, Stormie Mills comes to Sydney with an exhibition of graffiti and street based art of today. The work has undertakings of spray cans and alludes to night painting escapades.

version.name: Stormie Mills
version.description: Beginning on the street and going on to exhibit artwork the world over, Stormie Mills comes to Sydney with an exhibition of graffiti and street based art of today. The work has undertakings of spray cans and alludes to night painting escapades.

version.name: Mr Salmon and Mrs Sparrow
version.description: An unconventional map exhibition plotting the spread of Sydneysiders with fish- and bird-based surnames.

version.name: Soliloquy by Bill Brown
version.description: Brown has held more than 20 solo commercial exhibitions including at Rudy Komon Gallery, Rex Irwin Art Dealer and Macquarie Galleries. His return exhibition at Wilson Street Gallery in 2008 won accolades from peers, artists and critics. His work is held by all major Australian public and regional collections. His works have been described as depicting a place between places.

version.name: Bill Brown: Soliloquy
version.description: Brown has held more than 20 solo commercial exhibitions and his recent exhibition at Wilson Street Gallery in 2008 won accolades from peers, artists and critics. His work is held by all major Australian public and regional collections, and have been described as depicting a place between places.

version.name: Dinosnore Sleepover
version.description: Bring your kids to the Australian Museum's Dinosnore sleepover. The price includes a pizza, craft activities, a tour of the museum by torchlight, DVDs, and a night's sleep amongst dinosaur bones.

event.name: Ornithological Orchestra: Birds and their Calls

version.name: Ornithological Orchestra: Birds and their Calls
version.description: A provocative fast-paced lecture drawing on Dr Hollis Taylor's ornithological fieldwork.

version.name: TALK: Monsoons, mountains and mosquitoes
version.description: Dr Jodi Rowley talks about her expeditions through the remote forests of Indochina, where the frog fauna is relatively unknown, yet is still subject to human impacts through habit destruction and predation. Bookings essential.

version.name: Convict Sydney
version.description: The Hyde Park Barracks is one of Australia’s most important convict sites. This new exhibition explores the convict experience, from transportation to forging a new life in the colony of New South Wales. It reveals the extraordinary contribution convict workers made to the building of early Sydney. Learn about the everyday lives of convicts who passed through the doors of the barracks between 1819 and 1848.

version.name: Wit Large
version.description: Smart and literate comedy comes to Glebe's premier bookshop on the first Saturday of every month, with Tommy Dean, Lila Tillman and David Cunningham, plus your host Dr Dave Bloustien. The show also includes complementary wine and a book-browsing break.

version.name: Elif Bautman - Author Event
version.description: Elif Bautman brings tales of the scholarly and the ridiculous to life in her book The Possessed: Adventures with Russian books and the people who read them. Journey to the world of Dostoyevsky, Tolstoy and Chekhov, and the academics who worship them.

version.name: Satyajit Das - Author Event
version.description: Derivatives guru Satyajit Das warned of an impending financial meltdown in 2006. In the revised edition of his book he includes an afterword on the 2008 GFC but otherwise it is largely unchanged from his incendiary book from 2006. Now mired in a mess of our own making, this is a timely re-release of a book that correctly predicted the economic strife of the new millennium.

version.name: Fethiye Cetin - Author Event
version.description: Fethiye Çetin is a human-rights lawyer from Turkey who has defended many Turkish-Armenian people who have fallen victim to State and societal discrimination. Her book, My Grandmother, has been published in nine languages and examines identity, family and political history in Turkey.

version.name: Author Talk with Damien Pignolet
version.description: Damien Pignolet, head of Woollahra's prestigious Bistro Moncur and author of culinary tome French, is back with a new offering for burgeoning master chefs. In Salades, Pignolet explores the myriad of ways that one can interpret the humble salad so that is goes from supporting role to star attraction of the dinner table.

version.name: George Calombaris and Gary Mehigan
version.description: Its time for the MasterChef judges to put their money where their mouths are. Escorting readers into their own kitchens, both at work and at home, Calombaris and Mehigan demonstrate the skills, tricks and family favourites they have developed over their culinary careers with 43 of their favourite ingredients made into 86 delicious recipes. Selected recipes from the book will be served on the night so you can get a chance to judge the judges.

version.name: John Farnham
version.description: Luna Park celebrates its 75th anniversary with a special performance by Farnsey.

version.name: Judy Bailey
version.description: This week Jazz in the Cafe presents Judy Bailey.

version.name: Craig Scott
version.description: This week Jazz in the Cafe presents Craig Scott.

version.name: Salut! Baroque!
version.description: Folk meets baroque in this exposition of music by Monteverdi, Matteis, Marini, Falconieri, and Germiniani.

version.name: Flinders Quartet Program 2 - Beloved Beethoven
version.description: This performance signifies the end of the Con's journey through Beethoven's immense string quartet cycle, culminating in Op. 18 No. 2 in G as well as Op.59 No.1 in F.

version.name: The Merry Wives of Windsor
version.description: Die Lustigen Weiber Von Windsor features as part of the Con's season of Opera. Based on the original comedy by William Shakespeare, this opera in three acts is a European favourite sung in German.

version.name: Come and Play Gamelan
version.description: A workshop on the Indonesian percussion orchestra led by Associate Professor Peter Dunbar-Hall for the Friends of the Conservatorium. Audience members have a chance to participate.

version.name: Powderfinger - Sunsets tour
version.description: It's their last ever tour, everyone - after 20 years Powderfinger ride off into the Sunsets (see what we did there) for the final time. Their pals Jet are also on the bill.

version.name: Celtic Woman
version.description: For the first time ever, the multi-platinum Irish singing sensations (ocalists Lisa Kelly, Chloë Agnew, Lynn Hilary, Alex Sharpe and fiddler Máiréad Nesbitt) play the nation's stadia in support of Songs from the Heart.

version.name: Gorillaz
version.description:
Which actual humans are coming down our way remains a tantalising mystery at the moment (aside from Damon Albarn, one presumes…), but rest assured that Murdoc, 2D, Noodle and Russel will be represented.
Gorillaz from gladiator on Vimeo.

version.name: Ben 10 Live
version.description: The Australian premiere of Cartoon Network's BEN 10 LIVE: Power of the Omnitrix arrives in Sydney in September. Everyone's favourite boy-hero, Ben Tennyson, and his alien heroes will come to life on stage in BEN 10 LIVE, a show filled with stunts, action and special effects. Did somebody say 'Hero Time'?

version.name: Creedence Clearwater Revisited
version.description: The Fogerty brothers may be long gone, but the original Creedence Clearwater Revival rhythm section of Stu Cook and Doug "Cosmo" Clifford lead this new band in a selection of their old hits.

version.name: Enter Shakiri
version.description: Finally getting around to visting in support of last year's Common Dreads, the noisy electro-punks hit the Roundhouse with locals House vs Hurricane.

version.name: Soulfly, City of Fire, Incite
version.description: Max "Sepultura" Cavelera brings the monster metal of Soulfly our way in support of Omen, with City of Fire (featuring members of Strapping Young Lad and Fear Factory) and Incite for one hell of a loud night.

version.name: Cabins
version.description: After a massive year touring with Alberta Cross and the Soft Pack, Cabins are making a pretty impressive name for themselves as a band to keep an eye on. Touring with their album A Bright Victory, supported by Step-Panther, this is a show that showcases the future of Australian music.

version.name: Kontrast
version.description: Get your old school boogie on with Kontrast featuring Joey Kaz and Joey Tupaea.

version.name: Jackin
version.description: Hit up Jackin at Melt for a night of DJ battles with Ilya & Matt Roberts B2B, Travis Hale v Emme Jay, 2 Phat DJS v Hannah Gibbs, Ant Best v Rob Marshall, Funkinsteele v DJ Nycks, and Deefloy

event.name: Belly Dance and Arabic Music Extravaganza 2010

version.name: Belly Dance and Arabic Music Extravaganza 2010
version.description: Iconic Egyptian belly dancer, Dina, is the star performer at the three-day Belly Dance and Arabic Music Extravaganza. As well as performing as the feature act, Dina will also be looking on as judge for the Belly Dance Star Awards. There will also be dance workshops and stalls in a Cairo-like bazaar during the festival.

version.name: Margaret Woodward
version.description: A collection of the artist's paintings and drawings using oil, graphite, pastel, charcoal and more. Several subjects are explored with a mix of the exotic and domestic running side by side.

version.name: Parramasala
version.description: Colourful and uplifting, this new festival features a rich program of free and ticketed event. Innovative collaborations from today’s most celebrated, contemporary artists working across music, dance, theatre, film and visual arts.Full program and tickets available in August.

version.name: Parramatta Park Open Day
version.description: Parramatta park is hosting a fun family day. Explore Governor Macquarie’s surviving dairy cottage, see farm animals, learn how butter and lemonade are made, play colonial games, milk a cow or simply relax with a picnic in the beautiful parklands.

event.name: Roses in the Lumber Yard Heritage Rose Festival

version.name: Roses in the Lumber Yard Heritage Rose Festival
version.vendor-category: Around Town | Fairs & Festivals | Classes, Workshops & talks
version.description: Listen to talks by old tools expert Ralf Hawkins, rose expert Gillian Batchen and park curator Verena Mauldon, try your hand at sustainable gardening with Adrian Bligh or relax in the garden and take in the festival's jazz band over a picnic.

version.name: Jim Davidson
version.description: Jim Davidson is firmly established as one of Britain’s top stand-up comedians and the host of BBC TV game shows Generation Game and Big Break. He is bringing his comedy show back to Australia after last years tour for another bite at the apple. Kids be warned, this is an 18+ event.

version.name: Soundwave 2011
version.description: Yep, Soundwave has a date and (most likely, still to be entirely confirmed) location, not to mention a leaked line-up that includes Iron Maiden, Slayer, Gang of Four, Slash, Queens of the Stone Age, Slayer, Primus, Social Distortion, Rob Zombie, Avenged Sevenfold, Stone Sour, Pennywise, Sum 41, Third Eye Blind, Monster Magnet, The Gaslight Anthem, High on Fire, I See Stars, Nonpoint, Breathe Carolina, 36 Crazyfists, The Bronx, Alesana, 30 Seconds to Mars, Kylesa, Bayside, Asking Alexandria, The Sword, A Skylit Drive, Mad Caddies, There For Tomorrow, Veara, Less than Jake, All That Remains, Trash Talk, The Ataris, Protest The Hero and The Blackout. Whooo!

version.name: The Bushland Shire Festival
version.description: Head south for live shows by Channel Nine's New MacDonald's Farm, a historical vehicle display, market and food stalls, a scarecrow competition, animal farm, eco-gardening workshops, art demonstrations, and plenty of kids' activities.

event.name: Pochee/Robson Duo, Mute Canary Project - Steve Lacy Tribute

version.name: Pochee/Robson Duo, Mute Canary Project - Steve Lacy Tribute
version.description: The evening starts with a collaboration between improv masters, John Pochee on drums and Andrew Robson on sax, and ends with a tribute to Steve Lacy, courtesy of Brisbane's Mute Canary Project.

event.name: Sandy Evans Trio with Sarangan Sriranganathan & Bobby Singh, The Vampires

version.name: Sandy Evans Trio with Sarangan Sriranganathan & Bobby Singh, The Vampires
version.description: Saxophonist Sandy Evans jams with Bobby Singh on tabla and Maestro Sarangan Sriranganathan for an afternoon of energetic, Indian-infused jazz music.

version.name: Steve Hunter Quartet
version.description: Bassist Steve Hunter and his crew returns to the Sound Lounge for a powerhouse evening of new compositions.

version.name: Virna Sanzone Band
version.description: Pianist Tom O’Halloran, bassist Brett Hirst and other top-of-the-line players accompany Virna Sanzone and her sweet, silky vocals.

version.name: Scribe
version.description: New Zealand's finest rapper comes down under.

version.name: CSI Misunderstood?
version.description: Forensic experts explain how real crime scene investigations happen.

version.name: Bathurst 1000 V8 Supercars
version.description: Mt Panorama, Bathurst- the 'Mecca of Motorsport'. Watch the V8 Supercars come alive again with this must-see event.

version.name: Manly Arts Festival
version.description: The 16th anniversary of the community arts festival brings together over 60 events in the areas of art exhibitions, music, literature, theatre, dance, and performance by local and regional participants.

version.name: Woollahra Small Sculpture Prize
version.description: The only national acquisitive prize that showcases the quality and diversity of sculptures of smaller dimensions.

version.name: Form + Woollahra Small Sculpture Prize
version.description: The artists in Form take paper as their material starting point for their small sculptures.

version.name: Form
version.description: The artists in this group show take paper as their material starting point for their small sculptures.

version.name: Graham Kuo
version.description: A retrospective exhibition traces the silkscreen work of Graham Kuo, one of Australia's pre-eminent abstract expressionist printmakers.

event.name: Sydney 2000 Olympics and Paralympics 10th Anniversary Celebrations

version.name: Sydney 2000 Olympics and Paralympics 10th Anniversary Celebrations
version.description: To mark 10 years from the Sydney 2000 Olympics, a week long celebration will take place, including an exhibition of memorabilia at the Powerhouse Discovery Centre and the official relighting of the Olympic cauldron by Cathy Freeman.

event.name: Sydney Telstra 500 with Guns n' Roses

version.name: Sydney Telstra 500 with Guns n' Roses
version.description: Axl Rose and his band of hired guns hits Olympic Park as headliner of the V8 Supercars Sydney Telstra 500 weekend.

version.name: Mirah
version.description: For the first time ever - EVER - US indie folk chanteuse Mirah comes to Australia, joined by The Smallgoods and Shiver Me Timbers, in support of last year's beautiful (A)spera.

version.name: Women of Letters
version.description: If you long for the days of a hand-addressed envelope, penmanship and the excitement of the postman's daily appearance then make sure you get tickets to Women of Letters for their one-off Sydney, afternoon event. Celebrate the lost art of the letter with readings from Tara Moss, Jennifer Byrne, Claudia Karvan, Sally Seltman, Sacha Horley, and Virginia Gay, and raise money for Edgar's Mission Animal Shelter

version.name: Opera In The Caves
version.description: The Jenolan Caves is soon to be transformed into the Opera House of the Blue Mountains as part of a bold new concept in operatic performance.

version.name: Opera in the Vineyards
version.description: A journey through the life and times of Mozart's musical genius, led by performers in full period costume in surrounds of the vineyards.

version.name: Farewell BBQ
version.description: What's a farewell without a few thick ones thrown in your bun? Say goodbye to Bear Pride Week by taking in some meat.

version.name: 7th Australian Poetry Festival
version.description: A three-day festival of all things poetry. The line-up includes talks and workshops with Chris Wallace-Crabbe, Emily Ballou, David Brooks, John Bennett, Michael Farrell, Lucy Dougan and Paul Magee.

version.name: The Rock Show
version.description: Renee French, an American graphic novelist, and Shelley Burnham, an Australian painter, exhibit drawings and acrylic paintings of rocks, pebbles and stones. French covers hers in thin, flesh-like sheaths while Burnham offers simple and colourful forms.

version.name: The Big Bang
version.description: The Big Bang is White Rabbit’s third exhibition. Featuring an exhilarating selection of contemporary art, the highlights of the new show include Ai Weiwei’s 500-kilo pile of porcelain sunflower seeds, Li Hongbo’s enormous installation: a slinky-like paper man, and Wang Zhiyuan’s 11-metre-high whirlwind of rubbish. Located in the inner-city suburb of Chippendale.

version.name: Britpop's Third Birthday
version.description: It's been three years of Britpop goodness – oh, how the time flies! – and the team are in the mood to party, with Johnny Darko joined by El Mariachi, Johnny Segment, Urby and Time Out Sydney's own Andrew P Street.

version.name: Dei El-Ayoubi - Begin
version.description: An installation piece and a series of photographs that look at the physical experience of being in the womb.

version.name: Michael Gray - +8GMT
version.description: Divided from the subject by a language barrier, these photographs result from an unspoken barter system.

event.name: Tim Andrew - Where's my private jet

version.name: Tim Andrew - Where's my private jet
version.description: Brightly humorous, these images deal with life's downbeat anxieties.

version.name: Arthur Boyd: A Final Look
version.description: The final solo exhibition of Arthur Boyd's paintings as well as copper and ceramic works.

version.name: Coaster 2010
version.description: Gosford, get ready: you're going to get rocked by Cypress Hill, Birds of Tokyo, Art vs Science, Silversun Pickups, Bluejuice, Basement Birds, Cloud Control, Hungry Kids of Hungary, Boy & Bear, ILly, Spit Syndicate, The Aston Shuffle, The Holidays, The Chemis, City Riots, Slow Down Honey and many more! Grab tickets while you can, kids.

version.name: Freshley Squeezed
version.description: A night of new media performance from the new performance collective stagejuice. There will be puppetry, beat poetry, movement and theatre.

version.name: Freshly Squeezed
version.description: A night of new media performance from the new performance collective stagejuice. There will be puppetry, beat poetry, movement and theatre.

version.name: Intersection
version.description: This outdoor show from Milk Crate Theatre, which features performers who have experienced homelessness, is an interactive tour, part Greek tragedy and part exploration of turning points.

version.name: HCB 15th Anniversary Dinner
